<DOC><DOCNO> AP890209-0110 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1407EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-CommissionerPlea     02-09 0206</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Commissioner Plea,0214</SECOND><HEAD>Highway Commissioner Pleads Guilty To Extortion</HEAD><DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A former state highway commissioner todaypleaded guilty to extorting a $127,000 payoff from a constructioncompany.   Sam Waggoner, 67, of Newton, also pleaded guilty to filing falsefederal income tax returns. A highway commissioner for 21 yearsuntil he resigned Dec. 31, Waggoner could receive up to 29 years inprison and $550,000 in fines.   No sentencing date was set.   Prosecutors said the former commissioner of Mississippi's centralhighway district has agreed to testify in other white-collar crimecases.   A related FBI investigation of purchasing practices has resultedin corruption charges against 57 county supervisors in 26 counties.   Fifty-two have been convicted or have pleaded guilty, and theLegislature overhauled county purchasing practices to lessen thepotential for graft.   Waggoner pleaded guilty to accepting cash from Freddy Rogers ofFreddy Rogers Construction Inc. of Morton and underreporting hisincome by $190,500 in 1984-86.   On Wednesday, a judge sentenced former Southern District HighwayCommissioner Bob Joiner to six years in prison for extortion andfined the 59-year-old Waynesboro man $100,000 for tax evasion.   The third member of the state Highway Commission, NorthernDistrict Commissioner Zack Stewart, hasn't be charged with any crime.</TEXT></DOC>